{
  "focus": "proof-critique",
  "target_id": "ps_001",
  "target_type": "proof_summary",
  "verdict": "address_first",
  "strengths": [
    "Correctly held the tier at Probable rather than Proved, and stated why — all three underlying sources (src_001, src_002, src_003) are derivative indexes and original records were never pulled. This honors GPS standards rather than reaching for the more satisfying tier.",
    "The Correlation section does real independence work: named the three distinct informant/institutional origins (tax assessor, census enumerator, cemetery memorialist) and three separated dates rather than merely asserting 'multiple sources agree.'"
  ],
  "must_address": [
    {
      "standard": "Standard 43 — evidence integrity / Standards 64-67 — tier defensibility",
      "issue": "The 1840 census identification (a_001, a_002, pe_001, pe_002) is the pivot record for the whole proof — the only evidence placing the subject in Ohio at the exact contested mid-window date. Its match_score is 0.128, and pe_001's rationale explains the low score away (no birth year in the index) rather than corroborating identity through an independent channel. No household composition was checked, and the original image (ark:/61903/1:2:1TLM-646) was never examined even though it could resolve this directly.",
      "what_would_change_my_mind": "Pulling the original 1840 census household image and checking whether the other household members' ages/names are consistent with Christiana's known children would confirm or refute the identification independent of the uninformative match score.",
      "suggested_skill": "research-plan",
      "specific_action": "Add a plan item to examine ark:/61903/1:2:1TLM-646 directly; if household composition corroborates, upgrade pe_001/pe_002 confidence language accordingly and note the corroboration in ps_001."
    }
  ],
  "consider_addressing": [
    {
      "standard": "Standard 14 (topical breadth) / BCG peer-review test — unaddressed alternative",
      "issue": "The proof's own Background paragraph raises a specific competing hypothesis — 'possibly following one or more of her children who settled in that region' — and then the narrative never returns to test it. A peer reviewer will notice a hypothesis introduced and dropped.",
      "specific_action": "Either strike the children-in-Wisconsin line from Background if it's not being tested, or add a one-line note in Correlation stating whether any of Christiana's children were traced to Green County (and if not researched, say so as an open question rather than leaving it as unaddressed color)."
    }
  ],
  "non_blocking_notes": [
    "The 'no Wisconsin record found' point is stated twice — once under Evidence #2, again under 'Absence of Conflicting Evidence' — consider consolidating for a tighter read."
  ],
  "narrative_for_user": "# Mentor review: proof-critique on ps_001\n\n## What you have done well\nYou resisted the pull toward the more satisfying tier. The narrative explicitly names why this stays at Probable rather than Proved — all three sources are derivative indexes and the originals were never pulled — which is Standard 43 in action. Your Correlation section also does real independence work: naming the tax assessor, census enumerator, and cemetery memorialist as distinct informants under distinct institutional mandates across three separated dates is exactly the kind of specific reasoning that distinguishes a real proof from a source list.\n\n## What to address before moving on\nThe soft spot is the 1840 census identification (a_001, a_002, pe_001, pe_002) — and it matters more than it might look like, because it is the only record placing Christiana at the exact midpoint of the 15-year Ohio-to-death window (1834 to 1849). Everything else brackets that window; this record is what closes it. Its FamilySearch match score is 0.128, and pe_001's rationale explains that away (the census index lacks a birth year, so the algorithm had too little to work with) rather than corroborating identity some other way. The original household image (ark:/61903/1:2:1TLM-646) was never examined — and it is exactly the kind of record that could settle this: if the other household members' ages line up with Christiana's known children, the identification stands on much firmer ground than a dismissed match score.\n\n## Worth considering\nYour own Background paragraph raises the possibility that Christiana followed children to Green County, Wisconsin — and then the proof never comes back to that thread. A peer reviewer will notice a hypothesis raised and abandoned. Either drop the line, or add a sentence in Correlation noting whether this was checked.\n\n## What would change my mind\nPull the original 1840 census image and check household composition against Christiana's known children. If it corroborates, say so explicitly in ps_001 and the identification confidence language strengthens accordingly."
}

